==Summary of operation==
;Day 1 <U+2013> 19 March 2011
On the afternoon of 19 March, the Royal Navy {{sclass|Trafalgar|submarine}} {{HMS|Triumph|S93|6}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1368028/Cruise-strike-hits-Gaddafi-We-stand-let-dictator-murder-people.html?ito=feeds-newsxml |date=21 March 2011 |accessdate=21 March 2011 |title=RAF strikes against Gaddafi's forces branded 'a success' as bombed out tanks and cars litter the roads near Benghazi |author=Daily Mail Reporters |work=Daily Mail}}</ref> fired [[Tomahawk (missile)|Tomahawk]] cruise missiles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/BritishArmedForcesLaunchStrikeAgainstLibyanAirDefenceSystems.htm|title=British Armed Forces launch strike against Libyan Air Defence systems|accessdate=19 March 2011|date=19 March 2011|publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]]}}</ref> A combined total along with US over the day was reported by the US to be over 110 missiles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/world-news/africa/us-fires-110-missiles-as-nofly-zone-is-enforced-2586278.html|title=US fires 110 missiles as no-fly zone is enforced|accessdate=20 March 2011|date=20 March 2011|work=[[Irish Independent]]}}</ref>
The Royal Navy also has a [[Type 22 frigate]] ({{HMS|Cumberland|F85|6}}) and a [[Type 23 frigate]] ({{HMS|Westminster|F237|6}}) engaged in a [[naval blockade]].

[[David Cameron]], Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, confirmed that British aircraft were in action over Libya on the 19th,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-12796972|accessdate=19 March 2011|title=Libya: Coalition launches attacks from air and sea|publisher=BBC News|date=19 March 2011}}</ref> although it was the [[French Air Force]] who made the first coalition aerial presence over Libya earlier the same day.

Sentry, Sentinel and VC-10 aircraft were said to be carrying out operations from [[RAF Akrotiri]] in Cyprus.<ref name="MoDLibyaupdate" /> The home base for the VC-10 aircraft was [[RAF Brize Norton]] in Oxfordshire and for the Sentinel and Sentry aircraft was [[RAF Waddington]] in Lincolnshire.

On the night of 19<U+2013>20 March 2011, [[Storm Shadow]] missiles were launched by Tornado GR4 aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.monstersandcritics.com/news/africa/news/article_1627376.php/British-jets-fired-on-Libyan-targets |title=British jets fired on Libyan targets |date=20 March 2011 |publisher=monstersandcritics.com |agency=Deutsche Press Agentur}}</ref> Tornados of [[No. 9 Squadron RAF|No. 9 Squadron]] from [[RAF Marham]] had sortied on a {{convert|3000|mi|km|abbr=on|adj=on}} mission to fire Storm Shadow missiles against targets in Libya. They required refuelling by British tanker aircraft three times on the outward journey and once on the return. Tristar aircraft were involved.<ref>{{cite |url=http://www.edp24.co.uk/news/target_libya_raf_reveals_marham_jets_3_000_mile_mission_as_aircraft_prepare_to_deploy_to_italy_1_835355 |title=TARGET LIBYA: RAF reveals Marham jets<U+2019> 3,000-mile mission, as aircraft prepare to deploy to Italy |date=20 March 2011 |work=edp24.co.uk }}</ref>

;Day 2 <U+2013> 20 March 2011
The MoD announced that Tornado and Typhoon aircraft would be deployed to the Italian [[Gioia del Colle Air Base]].<ref name="MoDLibyaupdate"/>

The [[Trafalgar class submarine|''Trafalgar''-class submarine]] {{HMS|Triumph|S93|6}} launched further [[Tomahawk (missile)|Tomahawk]] cruise missiles at targets in Libya.<ref name="MoDLibyaupdate"/>

Tornados GR4s, flying from Marham, were about to attack a target but did not fire their missiles due to reports of civilians near the target.<ref name=libassets>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/UpdatedSecondUkStrikeAgainstLibyanDefenceAssets.htm |title=Updated: Second UK strike against Libyan defence assets |publisher=Ministry of Defence |date=21 March 2011}}</ref>

;Day 3 <U+2013> 21 March 2011
The Prime Minister announced to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] on 21 March at the start of the debate on the UNSC resolution that RAF Typhoons had been deployed to an Italian airbase (Gioia del Colle) and would fly in support of the NFZ.<ref>{{cite hansard |jurisdiction=United Kingdom |house=House of Commons |url=http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm110321/debtext/110321-0001.htm#1103219000645 |date=21 March 2011 |column_start=700 |column_end=701 |speaker=David Cameron |position=Prime Minister}}</ref> Three Typhoons successfully conducted a mission and returned to Gioia del Colle.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-12776418 |title=Live: Libya crisis |accessdate=22 March 2011 |date=22 March 2011 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>

Headquarters 906 Expeditionary Air Wing formed at [[Gioia del Colle Air Base]] responsible for assets forward deployed there.  Headquarters 907 Expeditionary Air Wing formed at [[RAF Akrotiri]] responsible for assets forward deployed there. [[Boeing C-17 Globemaster III|C-17A Globemaster]] and [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|Hercules]] transport aircraft were also used to assist in the build up of deployed forces.<ref name=opscontinue/>

;Day 4 <U+2013> 22 March 2011
RAF Typhoons flew their first ever combat mission,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/RafTyphoonsPatrolLibyanNoflyZone.htm|title=RAF Typhoons patrol Libyan no-fly zone|publisher=Ministry of Defence |date=22 March 2011}}</ref> patrolling the no-fly zone while Tornado GR4s from [[RAF Marham]] flew an armed reconnaissance sortie. The MoD reported that Royal Navy ships ''Triumph'', ''Westminister'' and ''Cumberland'' remained in theatre for additional strikes and patrol.<ref>{{cite web |title=Operations in Libya having a very real effect |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/OperationsInLibyaHavingAVeryRealEffect.htm |publisher=Ministry of Defence |date=22 March 2011}}</ref>

;Day 5 <U+2013> 23 March 2011
Tornado GR4s were forwarded deployed to Gioia del Colle Air Base.<ref name="LibyanAirForceNeutered">{{cite web|url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/LibyanAirForceNeutered.htm|title=Libyan air force neutered|publisher=Ministry of Defence |date=24 March 2011 |accessdate=24 March2011}}</ref> In a media interview, the UK Air Component Commander, Air Vice-Marshal Greg Bagwell, stated that the Libyan Air Force "no longer exists as a fighting force" and that "we have the Libyan ground forces under constant observation and we attack them whenever they threaten civilians or attack population centres."<ref>{{cite web |title=Libya air force 'unable to fight'|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-12837330 |publisher=BBC News |date=23 March 2011 |accessdate=23 March 2011}}</ref>

;Day 6 <U+2013> 24 March 2011
Tomahawk Cruise Missiles were again fired at targets from  HMS ''Triumph''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/BritishSubmarineLaunchesFurtherStrikesOnLibyanAirDefenceSystems.htm |title=British submarine launches further strikes on Libyan air defence systems |publisher=Ministry of Defence |date=24 March 2011 |accessdate=24 March 2011}}</ref>
RAF Tornado aircraft on an armed reconnaissance mission launched [[Brimstone (missile)|Brimstone]] missiles against Libyan armoured vehicles that were reported to be threatening the civilian population of Adjdabiya. Four [[T-72]] tanks were destroyed in the attack by Tornados, and three by another coalition aircraft.  Likely target locations had previously been identified by other Tornado aircraft equipped with [[RAPTOR]] pods.<ref name="OperationalUpdateOnLibya25March"/>

;Day 7 <U+2013> 25 March 2011
RAF Tornado aircraft launched more Brimstone missile strikes, destroying three armoured vehicles in Misrata and two further armoured vehicles in Ajdabiya.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/BrimstoneMissilesDestroyArmouredVehiclesInLibya.htm |title=Brimstone Missiles Destroy Armoured Vehicles in Libya|publisher=Ministry of Defence |date=26 March 2011 |accessdate=27 March 2011}}</ref>

;Day 9 <U+2013> 27 March 2011
Over the weekend, Tornados from Gioia del Colle launched numerous armed reconnaissance missions, during the course of which ordnance released hit a total of 22 tanks, armoured vehicles and artillery pieces in the vicinity of [[Ajdabiya]] and [[Misurata]].<ref name=furthertargets>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/RafStrikesFurtherTargetsInLibya.htm|title=RAF Strikes Further Targets in Libya |date=28 March 2011 |accessdate=28 March 2011 |publisher=Ministry of Defence}}</ref>

;Day 10 <U+2013> 28 March 2011
Tornados from RAF Marham, supported by Tristar tankers from RAF Brize Norton, launched Storm Shadow strikes against ammunition bunkers in the [[Sabha]] area in the southern Libyan desert. The bunkers were reportedly used to resupply Libyan Government troops attacking civilians in the north of the country.<ref name=furthertargets/>

;Day 11 <U+2013> 29 March 2011
The London Conference on Libya was chaired by the Foreign Secretary, [[William Hague]].

Two Tornados flying from Gioia del Colle engaged near [[Misurata]] a Libyan armoured fighting vehicle and two artillery pieces with [[Brimstone missile|Brimstone]] missiles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/DefencePolicyAndBusiness/LibyaConferenceParticipantsCommittedToMilitaryAction.htm|title=Libya Conference Participants Committed to Military Action |date=30 March 2011 |accessdate=31 March 2011 |publisher=Ministry of Defence}}</ref>

;Day 12 <U+2013> 30 March 2011
Tornados flying from Gioia del Colle engaged near Misurata three Libyan tanks, two armoured fighting vehicles and a [[surface-to-air missile]] site with Brimstone missiles and [[Paveway IV]] bombs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/RafAndNavyPatrolLibyanSkiesAndSeas.htm|title=RAF and Navy Patrol LIbyan Skies and Seas |date=31 March 2011 |accessdate=31 March 2011 |publisher=Ministry of Defence}}</ref> {{HMS|Liverpool|D92|6}} was deployed to relieve HMS ''Cumberland''.<ref name="portsmouth.co.uk"/>

;Day 13 <U+2013> 31 March 2011
From 06:00 GMT, [[NATO]] took sole command of air operations over Libya under [[Operation Unified Protector]], taking over from U.S. Africa Command.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/SID-4618E83B-9204E6B0/natolive/opinions_71897.htm|title=NATO Press Briefing|publisher=NATO|date=31 March 2011}}</ref><ref>http://www.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=59406</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defense.gov/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=63384|title=NATO Assumes Command of Libya Operations|publisher=Department of Defense|date=March 31, 2011}}</ref>

;Day 15 <U+2013> 2 April 2011
HMS ''Triumph'' returned to HM Naval Base Devonport flying the [[Jolly Roger]] marked for six successful Tomawhawk launches.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/HmsTriumphReturnsFromLibyaOperations.htm|title=HMS Triumph Returns from Libya Operations |date=4 April 2011 |accessdate=13 April 2011 |publisher=Ministry of Defence}}</ref>

RAF Tornado aircraft launched Paveway IV bombs against pro-Gaddafi forces. Two main battle tanks in [[Sirte]] and several small [[ground-attack aircraft]] on an airfield near [[Misurata]] were reportedly hit.<ref name="Ministry of Defence">{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/PmVisitsRafCrewsDeployedOnLibyaOperations.htm|title=PM Visits RAF Crews Deployed on Operations |date=5 April 2011 |accessdate=5 April 2011 |publisher=Ministry of Defence}}</ref>

;Day 16 <U+2013> 3 April 2011
RAF Tornados reportedly launched successful attacks with Paveway IV and Brimstone missiles on ten armoured fighting vehicles south of [[Sirte]].<ref name="Ministry of Defence"/>

;Day 17 <U+2013> 4 April 2011
The number of Tornado aircraft taking part in Operation Ellamy was increased from eight to twelve on 4 April, with the aircraft deployed from [[RAF Marham]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2011/apr/04/libya-uk-increase-tornado-jets | title=Libya: UK to increase number of Tornado jets | accessdate=4 April 2011 | date=4 April 2011 | publisher=The Guardian | archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5xhfkEfKz | archivedate=4 April 2011}}</ref>
RAF Tornados, engaged in two separate strikes in the Libyan city of [[Sirte]], launched three Brimstone missiles which destroyed one main battle tank and two surface-to-air missile launchers.<ref name="Ministry of Defence"/>

;Day 22 <U+2013> 9 April 2011
Seven tanks were destroyed by Tornado aircraft, two in Ajdabiya and five in Misrata, using [[Paveway IV]] bombs and [[Brimstone (missile)|Brimstone]] missiles.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-13023800 | title=Libya: RAF Tornados destroy seven Libyan tanks | accessdate=9 April 2011 | date=9 April 2011 | publisher=BBC News Online | archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5xp8jSTzK | archivedate=9 April 2011}}</ref>

;Day 23 <U+2013> 10 April 2011
The MoD reported that over the weekend of 22<U+2013>23 April, of 61 armoured vehicles and air defence assets destroyed by NATO, 21 were destroyed by RAF aircraft.<ref name="mod.uk">{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/TyphoonJoinsTornadoInLibyaGroundAttackOperations.htm |title=Typhoon joins Tornado in Libya Ground Attack Operations|publisher=Ministry of Defence |date=13 April 2011 |accessdate=13 April 2011}}</ref>

;Day 25 <U+2013> 12 April 2011
{{HMS|Turbulent|S87|6}} was declared available in theatre by the MoD for Tomahawk strikes should they be required.<ref name="mod.uk"/>

RAF Typhoon aircraft were used operationally in a ground attack role for the first time.  A Typhoon destroyed 2 main battle tanks near Misurata with Paveway II whilst a Tornado destroyed the third with Paveway IV.  In total, RAF aircraft destroyed eight main battle tanks on 12 April.  Since the start of Operation ELLAMY up until 12 April, RAF aircraft had engaged over 100 main battle tanks, artillery pieces, armoured vehicles and SAMs.<ref name="mod.uk"/>

;Day 31<U+2013>18 April 2011
RAF Tornados and Typhoons attacked a pair of multiple rocket launcher vehicles and a light artillery piece reportedly firing on Misurata, as well as a self-propelled gun and tank.<ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/DefencePolicyAndBusiness/UkMilitaryLiaisonAdvisoryTeamToBeSentToLibya.htm |date=19 April 2011 |accessdate=19 April 2011 |title=UK military liaison advisory team to be sent to Libya |publisher=Ministry of Defence}}</ref>

HMS ''Triumph'' was reported by the MoD to have launched two salvoes of Tomahawk missiles against command and control facilities alongside precision strikes by RAF Tornados, Typhoons and coalition aircraft.<ref name="ReferenceA"/> The MoD's previous report that HMS ''Triumph'' had returned to Devonport suggests the submarine involved was probably HMS ''Turbulent''.<ref name="mod.uk"/>{{Dubious|date=April 2011}}

;Day 32<U+2013>19 April 2011
The Foreign Secretary announced that a British Military Liaison Advisory Team was to be sent to Benghazi to advise the NTC on how to improve their military organisational structures, communications and logistics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/DefencePolicyAndBusiness/UkMilitaryLiaisonAdvisoryTeamToBeSentToLibya.htm |date=19 April 2011 |accessdate=20 April 2011 |title=UK military liaison advisory team to be sent to Libya |publisher=Ministry of Defence}}</ref>

;Day 48 - 5 May 2011
{{HMS|Brocklesby|M33|6}} destroyed a buoyant mine containing over 100&nbsp;kg of high explosive. Using her sonar and underwater mine disposal system, Seafox, the mine was destroyed one mile from the entrance to Misurata harbour.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/RoyalNavyClearsLibyanHarbourMine.htm |date=5 May 2011 |accessdate=9 May 2011 |title=Royal Navy Destroys Libya Harbour Mine|publisher=Ministry of Defence}}</ref>

;Day 49 - 6 May 2011
Tornados attacked a site south of Sirte based on analysis of intelligence by RAF Tactical Imagery Wing.  20 FROG-7 launchers and a significant number of Scud canisters were reported as either completely or partially destroyed. RAF aircraft also destroyed one tank and two armoured vehicles in the area of Misurata and one mobile rocket launcher south of Tripoli.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/RafDestroysGaddafiRocketLaunchers.htm |date=9 May 2011 |accessdate=9 May 2011 |title=RAF Destroys Gaddafi Rocket Launchers|publisher=Ministry of Defence}}</ref>

;Day 55 - 12 May 2011
An RAF Typhoon was reported to have destroyed two Palmaria 155mm howitzers near Sirte.<ref name="ReferenceB">{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/RafAndNavyStrikeTargetsInTripoli.htm |date=17 May 2011 |accessdate=17 May 2011 |title=RAF and Navy Strike Targets in Tripoli|publisher=Ministry of Defence}}</ref>

;Day 59 - 16 May 2011
Royal Navy Tomahawk missiles reportedly fired from HMS ''Triumph'', and Paveway IV bombs released by RAF Tornado aircraft were reported to have struck intelligence agency buildings and a training base used by Colonel Gaddafi's Executive Protection Force.  RN and RAF attacks were reported to have damaged or destroyed over 300 targets since the start of Operation Ellamy.<ref name="ReferenceB"/>

;Day 62 - 19 May 2011
Tornado GR4s attacked two corvettes in Al Khums naval base and destroyed a facility in the dockyard constructing fast inflatable boats which Libyan forces had reportedly used to mine Misurata and attack vessels in the area.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/RafStrikesGaddafisNavy.htm |date=20 May 2011 |accessdate=29 May 2011 |title=RAF Strikes Gaddafi's Navy|publisher=Ministry of Defence}}</ref>

;Day 63 - 20 May 2011
RAF aircraft destroyed five multiple rockets launchers around Tripoli.<ref name="ReferenceC">{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/RafDestroysMilitaryVehicleDepotInLibya.htm |date=26 May 2011 |accessdate=29 May 2011 |title=RAF Destroys Military Vehicle Depot in Libya|publisher=Ministry of Defence}}</ref>

;Day 67 - 24 May 2011
RAF aircraft attacked four armoured vehicles deployed near the Libyan city of Zlitan. A Tornado attacked a Libyan coastal radar station near Brega, which was destroyed with a dual-mode seeker Brimstone missile.<ref name="ReferenceC"/>

;Day 68 - 25 May 2011
A vehicle depot at Tiji was attacked by a Typhoon FGR4 and a Tornado GR4 dropping four Enhanced Paveway II and five Paveway IV weapons between them.<ref name="ReferenceC"/>

;Day 70 - 27 May 2011
{{HMS|Ocean|L12|6}} (detached from the Response Force Task Groups COUGAR 11 deployment) deployed with a complement of 4 [[AgustaWestland Apache|Apache]] helicopters to aid operations.<ref>http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/ApachesGetReadyToHelpProtectLibyanCivilians.htm</ref><ref>http://www.navynews.co.uk/news/1213-ocean-and-her-gunships-dispatched-to-libya.aspx</ref>

;Day 77 - 3 June 2011
The Response Force Task Group withdrew from COUGAR 11 and was deployed (A RFTG ship, HMS ''Ocean'' and her embarked Apache attack helicopters had been deployed days earlier) to supplement UK forces in Operation Ellamy.<ref>http://www.navynews.co.uk/news/1226-task-force-sent-to-libya-to-ratchet-up-the-pressure-on-gaddafi.aspx</ref>

